<section class="perf-section">
  <h2>Performance is the feature.</h2>
  <p>Forge is built Rust-first. The hot path never touches .NET.</p>
  <div class="perf-grid">
    <div class="perf-card">
      <div class="perf-stat">&lt;3s</div>
      <div class="perf-label">Cold start</div>
      <div class="perf-desc">First LSP response in under 3 seconds, including sidecar spawn and workspace load.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="perf-card">
      <div class="perf-stat">&lt;1ms</div>
      <div class="perf-label">Keystrokes</div>
      <div class="perf-desc">Tree-sitter re-parses the document incrementally on every keystroke. No lag. No stutter.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="perf-card">
      <div class="perf-stat">&lt;100ms</div>
      <div class="perf-label">Completions p50</div>
      <div class="perf-desc">Roslyn completions via the sidecar. Same engine as Visual Studio — faster round-trip.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="perf-card">
      <div class="perf-stat">&lt;500ms</div>
      <div class="perf-label">Diagnostics refresh</div>
      <div class="perf-desc">File-level diagnostic re-analysis after a keystroke, debounced at 150ms.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="perf-card">
      <div class="perf-stat">&lt;3s</div>
      <div class="perf-label">Crash recovery</div>
      <div class="perf-desc">If the Roslyn sidecar crashes, Forge respawns it automatically. Your editor never freezes.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="perf-card">
      <div class="perf-stat">&lt;1ms</div>
      <div class="perf-label">Cache hits</div>
      <div class="perf-desc">salsa incremental cache returns repeated hover and definition results in under a millisecond.</div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="features">
  <h2>Built different.</h2>
  <p>Not another half-baked extension. A ground-up reimagining of .NET developer tooling.</p>
  <div class="feature-grid">
    <div class="feature-card feature-highlight">
      <h3>Your editor. Your rules.</h3>
      <p>VS Code, Zed, Rider, Neovim, Emacs, Helix — Forge speaks LSP 3.17, so it works across editors. Stop letting Microsoft decide where you write code.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="feature-card">
      <h3>Solution Explorer that slaps.</h3>
      <p>A tree view that shows your whole solution — projects, files, NuGet packages, references — with right-click actions C# Dev Kit doesn't have. VS Code and Rider get native tool windows; Zed gets the same data through the Forge assistant command.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="feature-card">
      <h3>Rust host. Sub-millisecond parsing.</h3>
      <p>Tree-sitter incremental parsing in the Rust host. salsa-powered caching. Document symbols, folding, and selection ranges without waiting on Roslyn.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="feature-card">
      <h3>Full Roslyn. No compromises.</h3>
      <p>Completions, diagnostics, hover, go-to-definition — the complete Roslyn API. Same engine as Visual Studio, none of the lock-in.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="feature-card">
      <h3>Crash-proof architecture.</h3>
      <p>Sidecar process model means a Roslyn crash recovers in under 3 seconds. Your editor stays up. Your flow stays unbroken.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="feature-card feature-highlight">
      <h3>Zero. Vendor. Lock-in.</h3>
      <p>No licenses. No telemetry. No proprietary blobs. Fork it, extend it, ship it. This is the .NET tooling the community deserves.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="install">
  <h2>Get started.</h2>
  <pre><code>git clone https://github.com/MelbourneDeveloper/forge.git
cd forge
make install</code></pre>
  <p>Or install the VS Code extension from the <a href="/docs/">Getting Started</a> guide.</p>
</section>
